## ADB (Android Debug Bridge)

What it is: A command-line tool that allows communication with Android devices and emulators. While primarily for dynamic analysis, it's essential for static analysis workflows too.

## Key Features
  -Install/uninstall APKs on devices
  -Pull app data from devices
  -Access device shell
  -Extract app databases and SharedPreferences
  -View logs in real-time

## Primary use

# List connected devices
adb devices

# Install APK
adb install app.apk

# Pull app data (requires root or backup)
adb backup -f backup.ab com.example.app
adb pull /data/data/com.example.app/

# Check logs
adb logcat | grep -i "myapp"

## How ADB Helps Static Analysis:

1. Extract Installed Apps
  # List all installed packages
    adb shell pm list packages

  # Pull APK from device
    adb shell pm path com.example.app
    adb pull /data/app/com.example.app/base.apk

2. Access App Data (if backup enabled)
  # Check if backup is allowed (from static analysis)
  # Then extract data
    adb backup -f backup.ab com.example.app

  # Convert backup.ab to readable format using `abe` tool

3. Check Running Components
  # Verify if exported activities can be launched
    adb shell am start -n com.example.app/.MainActivity

  # Check exported services
    adb shell service list | grep example

4. View Runtime Behavior
  # Monitor logs while testing
    adb logcat -s "MyApp" -v time

  # Check if sensitive data is logged
    adb logcat | grep -E "password|token|api"

## ADB Security Considerations
  -Requires USB debugging enabled on device
  -Some operations need root access
  -Production apps shouldn't have debug flags
  -Use emulators for safe testing


